 Bowyer/Fletcher, Hunting.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Recommended Nonweapon Proficiencies.}{\fs24 
 Animal Lore, Endurance, Fire-Building, Jumping, Running, Survival, Tracking.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Equipment.}{\fs24 
 The Archer carries whatever other equipment she deems necessary.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Distinctive Appearance.}{\fs24 
 Archers have no distinctive appearance, aside from their trademark bows, which gleam with polish and loving care.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Special Benefits.}{\fs24 
 The Archer is an expert with her style of bow. In combat, the Archer may elect to do one of two things. She may either fire faster than most are able to, or she may use a bonus on trick shots.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {\fs24 \tab \tab If she elects to fire faster, she may take an extra shot every two rounds. That means the rate of fire becomes \tab \tab 
5/2, rather than the usual 2/1. This still includes her movement. If she chooses to stand still and fire, she may increase \tab \tab her rate of fire to 3/1; however, this enables enemy archers to target her more easily.
\par    \tab \tab If she elects to go with trick shots, she not only gains the usual bonus for specialization and high Dexterity, she \tab \tab also gains a +1 to each shot for every four experience levels.
\par    \tab \tab If the Archer keeps and cares for a bow for more than a month and keeps her arrows sharpened to a keen \tab \tab edge, she may cause 1 hp of additional damage when using these items. If using a different bow or new arrows, she \tab \tab 
does not gain the bonus. It can only be used with familiar, well-cared-for equipment.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Special Hindrances.}{\fs24 
 The Archer is limited in her choice of melee weapons, since she disdains them so much. She may choose only a long sword, short sword, and dagger. Even then, the Archer has a \endash 
1 penalty to attack rolls when using one of these weapons because she is unfamiliar with anything but the flight of an arrow.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {\fs24 \tab \tab Later weapon proficiencies may be devoted to other weapons, but the Archer will never gain a bonus to \tab \tab 
attack rolls with these weapons, despite any Strength or proficiency bonus. This includes losing the normal elven +1 \tab \tab to attack rolls with the long or short sword.
\par    \tab \tab The Archer must always be concerned about the quality of her bow and arrows. If any are faulty, she must \tab \tab repair them or replace them with equipment of higher quality. She can never use missile equipment of inferior \tab \tab quality
\emdash except when in mortal danger or when necessary for the success of a mission.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Wealth Options.}{\fs24 
 The Archer starts with 50 to 200 (5d4x10) gp and must buy her bow at 150% of the normal cost. This reflects the high quality and fine workmanship of the bow. She may use the rest of the money as she wishes to outfit herself.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Suggested Elf Subraces. }{\fs24 
Grey elf, high elf, sylvan elf.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {\fs24 
\par }{\b\fs24 WILDERNESS RUNNER
\par }{\fs24 There are rangers, and then there are rangers. Elves are uniquely connected with the rhythms of the forests, some more deeply than others. Only those who have chosen to become ran
gers may elect to become more fully part of the forest. They are called Wilderness Runners.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Role.}{\fs24 
 Wilderness Runners have cast aside the trappings of even elven society to serve the needs of the wood. Although they still respect and serve their own soci
ety, they take no part in its functions. They may serve as scouts or advance guards for elf cities, but they will not willingly enter civilization.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {\fs24    \tab \tab If the Wilderness Runner is a high elf, he is far less civilized than his brethren and demonstrates the tendencies of \tab \tab sylvan elves. 

\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Secondary Skills.}{\fs24  Trapper/Furrier.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Weapon Proficiencies.}{\fs24  }{\i\fs24 Bonus:}{\fs24 
 Quarterstaff, long bow. }{\i\fs24 Recommended:}{\fs24  Two-handed style, dagger, organic weapons.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Bonus Nonweapon Proficiencies.}{\fs24 
 Endurance, Running, Set Snares.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Recommended Nonweapon Proficiencies.}{\fs24 
 Fire-Building, Fishing, Hunting, Mountaineering, Survival, Swimming.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Equipment.}{\fs24 
 The Wilderness Runner is notable for his lack of encumbrance. He travels light whenever possible, preferring to own distance rather than material goods.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Distinctive Appearance.}{\fs24 
 Wilderness Runners never wear "civilized" clothes, preferring instead to dress in leather. They also tend to bathe only while swimming or if caught in a downpour. They do not care for the petty habits and concerns of city folk.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Special Benefits.}{\fs24 
 Wilderness Runners, like all rangers, gain the Tracking proficiency. However, because of their proximity to the land, they gain a +2 bonus and are usually far better trackers than their cousins.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {\fs24 \tab \tab Because of their constant exposure to the elements, they have inured themselves to all but the most extreme \tab \tab 
temperatures. Unless the air is below 32 degrees F or above 100 degrees F, Wilderness Runners feel nothing. The \tab \tab variation in temperature is merely a pleasant change.
\par    \tab \tab Runners can use the Set Snares proficiency to entrap people as can thieves. Their understanding of the ways to lure \tab \tab people and animals into these traps is rarely exceeded.
\par    \tab \tab Wilderness Runners never run out of equipment. Although they carry very little and need even less, they can fashion \tab \tab weapons and other working gear from organic materials with astounding speed. While their work may seem crude, it 
\tab \tab is functional and works as well as, or better than, much of the equipment manufactured by civilized folk.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Special Hindrances.}{\fs24 
 Wilderness Runners are acutely uncomfortable in civilization. Their need for fresh air and the freedom of the forest overwhelms them within one day unless they can make a Wisdom check at \endash 4. Past the second day, they cannot rem
ain within walls and must wait outside for their companions.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {\fs24 \tab \tab Likewise, they find it difficult to remain within dungeons, crypts, or other unnatural caverns for long. If a cave is \tab \tab 
natural, Wilderness Runners will be able to remain inside without having to make a Wisdom check. Even then, they \tab \tab do retain their claustrophobia and long for the open air.
\par    \tab \tab Wilderness Runners never use mounts. For one thing, mounts cannot move through the forests quickly enough for \tab \tab them. For another, the Runners respect animals too much to abuse them in such a fashion.
\par    \tab \tab Wilderness Runners are greeted with some contempt by civilized elves who, although they respect the abilities of the \tab \tab Wilderness Runners, sneer at their "backward" ways. Most civilized elves react at a \endash 
2 to Wilderness Runners. They \tab \tab will not be overtly hostile, but they will be unfriendly to any unwashed elves. Sylvan elves and their allies, however, \tab \tab will react to their unwashed Wilderness Runner cousins at a +2.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Wealth Options.}{\fs24  Wilderness Runne
rs start with 3 to 30 (3d10) gp. They must create the rest of their gear from natural sources. They scoff at material wealth and are unlikely to have more than 10 or 20 gp at any time.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Suggested Elf Subraces.}{\fs24  High elf, sylvan elf.

\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {\fs24 
\par }{\b\fs24 WINDRIDER
\par }{\fs24 Few mounted cavalry are as glamorous and exciting as the Windriders. The elite of the elf forces, they are greatly envied by common elves and greatly feared by foes.\tab 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Role.}{\fs24 
 The Windrider is the knight of the air, defending elf lands against aerial attacks. In times of war, they are both shock troops and scouts.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {\fs24 \tab 
The DM may not wish to allow Windriders in a campaign, for they vastly increase the scope of a PC's operations. Then, too, the Windrider's mount may very well make a low-level PC far more powerful than he o
r she ought to be. It is recommended that DMs thoroughly familiarize themselves with Windriders before allowing them into a campaign.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Secondary Skills.}{\fs24  Groom.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Weapon Proficiencies.}{\fs24  }{\i\fs24 Bonus:}{\fs24 
 Lance (Light, Medium, or Heavy\emdash one only). }{\i\fs24 Recommended:}{\fs24  Short bow, flail, long sword.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Bonus Nonweapon Proficiencies.}{\fs24 
 Air-Based Riding, Animal Handling (for mount's species only), Animal Training (for mount's species only).
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Recommended Nonweapon Proficiencies.}{\fs24 
 Astrology, Navigation, Direction Sense, Weather Sense.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Equipment.}{\fs24 
 Windriders must, of course, keep saddles and food for their mounts. Otherwise, Windriders are free to carry what they will if their mount can bear the burden.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Distinctive Appearance.}{\fs24  
When separated from their beloved mounts, Windriders do not appear much different from ordinary elves. They may be more haughty, but otherwise they appear as normal elves.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Special Benefits.}{\fs24 
 The Windrider is one of the few kits where players receive no b
enefits until reaching high levels. Likewise, they do not suffer the hindrances until they have reached this level, which is typically 4th to 6th level, although it can be later (or earlier, if the character is especially worthy). Those aspiring to be Win
driders must prove themselves worthy of this kit before actually being allowed entrance. They may not have a kit before becoming a Windrider.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {\fs24 \tab \tab Although they do not gain many benefits, the quality of their benefits is enough for the Windrider. First is the reaction \tab \tab 
bonus they receive from members of the higher classes in both elven and human society. When they are traveling with \tab \tab their mounts, Windriders gain a +2 reaction bonus when dealing with them.
\par    \tab \tab A more important benefit, however, is the mount. When admitted to the ranks of the Windriders, characters receive \tab \tab intensive training with a mount of the species available. They are effectively out of commission for one year while 
\tab \tab learning to be a Windrider. After that time they are full Windriders, and they gain a winged mount from one of the \tab \tab following races: griffon, hippogriff, or pegasus.
\par    \tab \tab Their choice of mount confers no other special ability except the ability to communicate, in a very basic fashion, with \tab \tab the members of the mount's speci
es. They also gain the mobility of flight and a companion who is prepared to defend \tab \tab them with its life.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Special Hindrances.}{\fs24 
 While they are respected by the higher social classes in elven society, Windriders are the object of great jealousy\emdash sometimes even hatred\emdash 
from the lower classes. Their arrogant manner and disregard for beings of a lower social status earn them the enmity of the lower classes. They suffer a \endash 3 penalty to their reaction rolls when dealing with these folk.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {\fs24 \tab \tab Though able to strike awe into their hearts, Windriders can also earn the enmity of humans. After the initial awe has \tab \tab 
worn away, Windriders suffer a \endash 3 penalty for reactions from lower-class humans.
\par    \tab \tab If his animal dies, the Windrider is temporarily without the benefits of this kit. Although he may eventually regain a \tab \tab 
mount, the loss is such that it causes him to suffer all of the hindrances without gaining any of the benefits of this kit.
\par    \tab \tab The major hindrance of the kit is also the major benefit. The Windrider must always be concerned with the welfare of \tab \tab his mount, for he would not be a Windrider without it. Constantly worrying about one's mount is the chief \tab 
\tab occupational hazard of the Windrider.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Wealth Options.}{\fs24 
 The Windrider begins with 60 to 240 (6d4x10) gp and can spend these as he pleases. However, he must ensure the care of his mount by finding it food and shelter or else lose the benefits of the kit when the animal flees its master to take care of itself.

\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Suggested Elf Subraces.}{\fs24 
 Grey elf, high elf, sylvan elf.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {\fs24 
\par }{\b\fs24\cf13 Mage/Thief Kits
\par }{\fs24 
\par Although they are not exactly common, elf mage/thieves have their own niche in elven society. Their magical abilities allow them to enter places normally
 denied to mere thieves, and their skills with physical objects can often spell the difference between life and death for many who depend on them.
\par 
\par }{\b\fs24 ELVEN MINSTREL
\par }{\fs24 Although not actually a mage/thief, the elven minstrel kit that originally appeared in }{\i\fs24 The Complete Bard's Handbook}{\fs24 
 has characteristics of both classes. In the interest of conserving space, it is not reprinted here. This elf version of the bard does exist for those who have been yearning to play just such a character.
\par 
\par }{\b\fs24 SPELLFILCHER
\par }{\fs24 This mage/thief is adept at breaking into wizard's domiciles to purloin magical goods, particularly spellbooks and rare spell components. Through a strange inner talent, the spellfilcher has an amazing ability.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Role}{\fs24 
. When there is a magical trap to be disarmed or magical treasure to be gotten, the Spellfilcher is the one to do it. Trained from her early years, the Spellfilcher uses an innate magical ability to locate and disarm traps that would victimize another.

\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Secondary Skills.}{\fs24  Jeweler, Scribe.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Weapon Proficiencies.}{\fs24  }{\i\fs24 Bonus:}{\fs24 
 None. }{\i\fs24 Recommended:}{\fs24  Short bow, dagger, darts, short sword.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Bonus Nonweapon Proficiencies.}{\fs24 
 Appraising, Spellcraft, Tightrope Walking.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Recommended Nonweapon Proficiencies.}{\fs24 
 Disguise, Gaming, Gem Cutting, Jumping, Rope Use, Tumbling.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Equipment.}{\fs24 
 The Spellfilcher always carries at least a minimal set of lockpicks and usually a full housebreaker's harness.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Distinctive Appearance.}{\fs24 
 Spellfilchers, by their very nature, do not want a distinctive appearance. They go out of their way to make themselves look like average elves, deliberately ridding themselves of any identifying habits.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Special Benefits.}{\fs24 
 The Spellfilcher is a special breed, selected from birth to be a mage/thief because of an exceptional inborn talent. This talent, }{\i\fs24 which can only be nurtured by the Spellfilcher Guilds}{\fs24 
, allows the Spellfilcher to detect magic once per day, per experience level. Infant elves are tested for their latent sensitivity to magic, something which only the masters of the Spellfilching Guilds can determine.
 If the infant shows promise, she is taken from her parents (with their permission) and the talent is nurtured into a usable skill.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {\fs24 \tab \tab The Spellfilcher learns to identify and circumvent magical traps. Although they cannot remove these traps without a \tab \tab }{\i\fs24 dispel magic}{
\fs24  spell or similar item, they can often get around them long enough to remove the items these wards were \tab \tab protecting. Thus, Spellfilchers gain a +5% chance to Find/Remove Traps of a magical nature. This chance increases \tab \tab 
by +5% every four levels. They do not actually remove the traps but disarm them for 1d4 rounds, +1 round per three \tab \tab levels, which should be enough for them to retrieve the item they seek.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Special Hindrances.}{\fs24 
 The Spellfilcher's first loyalty must always be to her guild. The guil
d demands total compliance with its rules, for it serves the elf race in its own way and demands that its members do so as well. Unfortunately, this service occasionally requires that the Spellfilcher be called away from whatever she may wish to do. If th
e Spellfilcher fails to heed the call, the wrath of the powerful guild descends upon her head.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {\fs24 \tab \tab The Spellfilcher's Guild will not, on the other hand, call a Spellfilcher away from a mission of dire importance to the elf \tab \tab 
race or a mission that the Spellfilcher claims is of extreme importance. Since Spellfilchers operate on an honor system, \tab \tab they trust her. If, however, too many excuses keep her from her duties, the Guild has a right to demand cooperation \tab 
\tab and will not tolerate excuses.
\par    \tab \tab To help keep discipline, the Spellfilcher must ask permission of the guildmaster before leaving on adventures. \tab \tab Depending on the Spellfilcher's past record and loyalty to the guild, the guildmaster may agree or disagree.
\par    \tab \tab The Spellfilcher character has a hard time dealing with non-elf mages. Once they discover who she is and what she \tab \tab does for a living, they simply do not trust her near their precious spellbooks and valued items. Elf mages trust \tab 
\tab Spellfilchers, for they know that the Spellfilcher does it for the good of the race and would not harm an elf wizard. \tab \tab Other wizards, however, are not so sure of this. For this reason, Spellfilchers take great pains to disguise themselves 
\tab \tab and their intentions.
\par    \tab \tab Spellfilchers also take great pains to disguise themselves because they are hunted by both vengeful wizards and \tab \tab greedy thieves. The wizards desire the return of their property and perhaps revenge on the one audacious enough to \tab 
\tab steal from them.
\par    \tab \tab Conniving thieves wish to find a Spellfilcher to either recruit her into their guild or to get her to work for them. Failing \tab \tab 
that, they want to discover the secret to the Spellfilcher's success and to exploit that secret. They will not accept the \tab \tab fact that hers is an inborn talent. Thieves can make a Spellfilcher's life chaos if she is discovered by their guild.

\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Wealth Options.}{\fs24 
 Spellfilchers receive 30 to 90 (2d4+1x10) gp, which can be spent as the Spellfilcher desires. There are no limits, but it is suggested that they purchase thieves' tools.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Suggested Elven Subraces.}{\fs24 
 Aquatic elf, drow, grey elf, high elf.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {\fs24 
\par }{\b\fs24\cf13 Fighter/Mage Kits}{\fs24 
\par 
\par Combining the offensive physical power of the warrior and the intelligence and magical abilities of the mage, these are truly fearsome fighters. They have knowledge\emdash not only of strategy and tactics\emdash 
but of magical theory and offense. They are vital to the elves.
\par    \tab It is important to note that fighter/mages can cast spells only when unarmored or clad in elvenmade or magical armor. All other armor is too unresponsive to the ways of magic for magic to flow through it properly.
\par 
\par }{\b\fs24 BLADESINGER
\par }{\fs24 Of the roving elves, there are few as deadly as the Bladesinger. They are masters of their weapons and have spent their lives in the study of th
eir chosen weapons. They have also learned to cast spells while engaged in combat, and thus they double their might.
\par    \tab To be a Bladesinger, a character needs at least a 13 Strength and Constitution, as well as a 15 Dexterity and Intelligence.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Role.}{\fs24 
 While some characters may stay at home to defend the elven way, Bladesingers go out and actively promote it. They do this by seeking out their race's foes and eliminating them, either through words or actions. Acting as both diplomats and one-elf armies,
 they insure the safety of the elf race.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Secondary Skills.}{\fs24 
 Hunter, Trader/Barterer, Trapper/Furrier.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Weapon Proficiencies.}{\fs24  }{\i\fs24 Bonus:}{\fs24 
 None. }{\i\fs24 Recommended:}{\fs24  One-weapon style for use in combat and spells; two-handed style for use when spells run out.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Bonus Nonweapon Proficiencies.}{\fs24 
 Blind-Fighting, Dancing.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Recommended Nonweapon Proficiencies.}{\fs24 
 Etiquette, Juggling, Singing, Tumbling, Weaponsmithing.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Equipment.}{\fs24 
 The Bladesinger is always identifiable by his weapon of choice. Such an item is always ornate and beautiful, enhancing the Bladesinger's appearance in battle.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Distinctive Appearance.}{\fs24 
 Not only are they easily identifiable by their weapon of choice and catlike grace, Bladesingers are decorated with their weapon guild's distinctive tattoo. Each guild
 has a separate and unique tattoo depicting its style of weapon through an animal representation. Long swords are often represented by great cats such as lions or panthers, a whip would be shown as a striking snake, and so forth.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Special Benefits.}{\fs24  There
 are four special benefits to the Bladesinger kit, as follows:
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {\fs24 \tab }{\b\fs24 1.}{\fs24  The Bladesinger chooses one weapon and practices with it extensively, to the exclusion of most other weapons. If \tab 
practice makes perfect, the Bladesingers are very well practiced in their weapon of choice\emdash for they are virtually perfect.
\par    \tab The poised steps of the bladesong (the act of attack by a Bladesinger) not only reveals the Bladesinger to be a creature of \tab beauty even during battle, but the steps also carry him into advantageous posit
ions for either offense or defense. He can \tab instinctively grasp the flow of the battle around him, and his feet will carry him through the intricate maneuvers necessary \tab to optimize his attack.
\par    \tab \tab Such is the intensive training of the Bladesinger that he gains an automatic +1 to attack rolls as well as a +1 for \tab damage. This is in addition to the normal elven +1 for use of the long or short sword (if applicable). Despite any \tab 
additional, further training, this is as high as the bonus can be.
\par    \tab }{\b\fs24 2.}{\fs24  Bladesingers receive a special bonus when they wish to try an unusual maneuver with their blade. This bonus is equal to \tab 
+1 for every four levels the Bladesinger has attained. The bonus only serves to cancel the penalties normally applied for \tab such a maneuver. All other penalties and bonuses still apply.
\par 
\par }{\b\fs24 EXAMPLE:}{\fs24  }{\i\fs24 Vilana Pyreen, a 5th-level Bladesinger proficient in the long sword, attempts to disarm her opponent (a special maneuver). Normally, this gives her a +1 to initiative and a \endash 
4 to attack rolls. Since she is a 5th-level Bladesinger, however, her bladesinging ability gains her a +1 on her disarm maneuver. Since she is an elf, she gains an additional +1 because she is using her sword. Finally, she gains a +1 for her blade-singing
 ability with her sword. Her total is only a \endash 1 to disarm her foe. If she were 12th level, she would have a +1 on her disarming attack.
\par }{\fs24    
\par \tab }{\b\fs24 3.}{\fs24  Bladesingers have been taught from an early age to grasp the flow of magic around them and to turn it to their \tab a
dvantage. They can cast spells even while in the front lines. Although they cannot actually attack while casting their spells, \tab they may defend themselves against incoming melee attacks.
\par    \tab \tab Their defense is equal to their level divided by 2, plus 1. All fractions are rounded down. Thus, a 6th-level \tab Bladesinger gains a +4 to AC (6th level/2=3+1=+4 AC). The same goes for 7th-level Bladesingers (7/2=3.5 \tab \endash 
.5=3+1=+4 AC). This does not apply to rear or missile attacks, for it is nearly impossible to defend against those while \tab casting a spell.
\par    \tab \tab Bladesingers have practiced the somatic portion of their spells well enough that they may cast their spells one-handed, \tab suffering only a slight penalty. It adds +2 to their casting times, making it easier to disrup
t their spells. Like any other \tab spellcaster, if they are hit they lose the concentration necessary for maintaining their spells; they lose the spell. Their spells \tab are, therefore, usually of an offensive nature with very short casting times.

\par    \tab }{\b\fs24 4.}{\fs24  The training is hard enough that only a 3rd-level Bladesinger can begin to teach even the rudiments of the bladesong. If \tab 
another elf wishes to learn the bladesong, he must seek one of the masters of the blade. Bladesingers charge a high price \tab for sharing their skills.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Special Hindrances. }{\fs24 
To offset their abilities, Bladesingers suffer some severe penalties. Not only must they attempt to advance the cause of elvendom somehow at all times, they must also lend aid to any elf in need. Unless the elf is proven to b
e an enemy of the elven way of life, the Bladesinger must sacrifice life and limb to save that elf's life.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {\fs24    \tab \tab Of course, the Bladesinger is free to determine whether there is, in fact, an elf in danger. Too many times other races \tab \tab 
have tried to eliminate the Bladesinger menace through illusion and trickery. The Bladesingers have grown wary and \tab \tab have, unfortunately, allowed fellow elves to perish while trying to determine the truth of the threat. Thus, most \tab \tab 
Bladesingers carry at least one }{\i\fs24 detect magic}{\fs24  spell in order to avoid possible errors.
\par    \tab \tab Bladesingers are so devoted to their chosen weapon that they can never learn another one. Unlike other elves, they \tab \tab do not gain a +1 to attack rolls with a bow. With all other weapons, they suffer a \endash 1 penalty
 to attack rolls, even if \tab \tab they have taken it as a proficiency. If they have not devoted the slot to learn the weapon, the Bladesinger suffers the \tab \tab ordinary nonproficiency in addition to the \endash 1 penalty.
\par    \tab \tab If the player is using }{\i\fs24 The Complete Fighter's Handbook}{\fs24 , he may not allow his character to specialize in weapon \tab \tab groups. The Bladesinger focuses on a single weapon only.
\par    \tab \tab Bladesingers may wear no armor heavier than elven chain or studded leather. Bulkier armor restricts the Bladesingers' \tab \tab movement enough that they have at least a \endash 
2 penalty to attacks if they try to use their bladesinging ability while \tab \tab wearing such armor. The penalty is greater for heavier armor, although this is at the DM's discretion.
\par    \tab \tab Bladesingers rarely use weapons other than swords. With only rare exceptions, they never learn two-handed fighting \tab \tab styles. They may not use shields or two-handed weapons, for these interfere with the bladesong. Even when they \tab 
\tab have run out of spells, Bladesingers will fight one-handed or with both hands on their single-handed weapon. To do \tab \tab otherwise negates all bladesinging bonuses.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Wealth Options.}{\fs24 
 Bladesingers start their adventuring lives with 30 to 180 gp (3d6x10), and only one restriction: They must purchase their weapon of choice.
 Any monies left after buying their initial equipment must be returned to the Bladesinger's Guild. Later in their adventures, they must take opportunities to upgrade their weapons. Other than these restrictions, they are free to do as they wish with their
 money.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Suggested Elf Subraces.}{\fs24  Grey elf, high elf.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {\fs24 
\par }{\b\fs24 WAR WIZARD
\par }{\fs24 Although elves do not desire war, preferring instead to live their lives in peace and idyllic happiness, they recognize that the world is full of races hostile to elves, all of whom would lo
ve to see them driven into the dirt. A War Wizard is one who has devoted her life to defending against such attacks.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Role.}{\fs24 
 The War Wizard is usually the person in charge of defense for any given elf town. When there is a problem with an enemy, the War Wizard is the one to call.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {\fs24    \tab \tab Even if not associated with a town, the War Wizard is an invaluable asset to any group that expects to face trouble. \tab \tab 
Simple strategic knowledge is her bread and butter, but her expertise does not end there. She can work offensive \tab \tab marvels physically, and her spellcasting skills are excellent.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Secondary Skills.}{\fs24  Scribe, Tactician.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Weapon Proficiencies.}{\fs24  }{\i\fs24 Bonus:}{\fs24 
 Long bow, long sword. }{\i\fs24 Recommended:}{\fs24  Short bow, short sword, weapon style specialization (from }{\i\fs24 The Complete Fighter's Handbook}{\fs24 ).
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Bonus Nonweapon Proficiencies.}{\fs24 
 Spellcraft, plus Engineering or Survival.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Recommended Nonweapon Proficiencies.}{\fs24 
 Blind-Fighting, Heraldry, Land-Based Riding, Languages (Ancient or Modern), Set Snares, Weather Sense.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Equipment.}{\fs24 
 A War Wizard can carry whatever equipment she likes.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Distinctive Appearance.}{\fs24 
 War Wizards have no distinctive appearance. They may dress as they please on their own time. However, they often have a military aura. When in a military capacity, they must wear a uniform.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Special Benefits.}{\fs24 
 The War Wizard, because of her knowledge of strategy, can enable her side to add +1 to their attack rolls for the duration of a battle. This bonus applies only if all the following conditions are met: 1) The War Wizard h
as had a chance to survey the area and map it. 2) The War Wizard holds a strategy meeting with all who gain the +1 bonus. 3) All members of the War Wizard's side who are to gain the bonus successfully make an Intelligence check that has been modified by t
h
e difficulty of the instructions and changes in the terrain. Those who fail do not gain the bonus, and they run the risk of destroying another team member's bonus during battle. If these conditions are met, the War Wizard's side gains the bonus. If any pa
rt is left out or ignored, the bonus is negated.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {\fs24    \tab \tab The War Wizard is allowed a weapon of choice. She gains a +1 to attack rolls with this weapon, cumulative with all \tab \tab 
other applicable bonuses.
\par    \tab \tab She also gains a "spell of choice," once every four levels. This spell is usually a large-scale, offensive spell or it may be \tab \tab 
a handy defensive spell. Only rarely are they personal in scope and, even then, it must have some applicability to a \tab \tab larger party. The spell can be of any level the War Wizard can cast at the time she chooses the spell. Thus, at the 4th \tab 
\tab level, a War Wizard can choose spells of the 1st or 2nd level. At the 8th level, she can choose spells of up to the 4th \tab \tab level.
\par    \tab \tab The chosen spell is not a bonus spell for the War Wizard. It must still be memorized as would a normal spell. \tab \tab However, the spell can be either cast more quickly, firing at a +1 to initiative, or force the opponent to take a \endash 
1 on \tab \tab his save. For every four levels the War Wizard has practiced this spell, she gains a +1 bonus to either side. For \tab \tab example, if a 12th-level War Wizard had chosen }{\i\fs24 sleep}{\fs24 
 as her spell at the 4th level, she would now gain either +2 to \tab \tab initiative when casting it or would cause her opponents to save at \endash 2.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Special Hindrances.}{\fs24 
 The War Wizard is limited in her choice of weapons. Although a warrior/mage ordinarily receives the full gamut of weapons, a War Wizard may only take certain weapons. Any of the normal wizard's weapons, any blade, an
y bow, or a lance may be chosen. The selection cannot extend beyond these, however.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {\fs24    \tab \tab War Wizards have a Code of Conduct that they must abide by at all times. Even when they are apart from their units, \tab \tab 
the code may never be broken. If it is and they are discovered, they will be drummed from the unit. It is up to the DM \tab \tab and the player to determine what the Code is for each unit, but it should fierce, demanding, and restrictive.\tab 
\par \tab \tab Finally, there are demands the unit will place on the War Wizard. She must comply with these demands or lose her \tab \tab benefits. The unit will typically take up about one month per year of the War Wizard's time.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Wealth Options.}{\fs24 
 The War Wizard has 30 to 180 (3d6x10) gp initially, which can be spent however she likes.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Suggested Elf Subraces.}{\fs24  Drow, grey elf, high elf.

\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {\fs24 
\par }{\b\fs24\cf13 Fighter/Thief Kit}{\fs24 
\par 
\par These are the toughest elves around (and the most quintessentially elven), for they rely on skill rather than muscle. Although warrior/thieves may not be truly adept with any weapon, their thie
f skills more than make up for that. Fighter/thieves are very useful in a campaign based more on subtlety than force.
\par 
\par }{\b\fs24 HUNTSMAN
\par }{\fs24 Although some call them bounty hunters, the Huntsmen know better. Their chief joy in life is the hunt, and they have trained themselves in the ways of life: fighting and stealth.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Role.}{\fs24 
 A Huntsman is at home in both the city and the wilderness. His job is to track down errant wrongdoers and bring them to justice. He can be good, evil, or neutral; he may ethically bring criminals 
to face the law or hunt them just for money. Whether he is good or not good, his motivation is more the thrill of the hunt than material gain.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Secondary Skills.}{\fs24  Trapper/Furrier.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Weapon Proficiencies.}{\fs24  }{\i\fs24 Bonus:}{\fs24 
 Net. }{\i\fs24 Recommended:}{\fs24  Blowgun, long bow, lasso, long sword.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Bonus Nonweapon Proficiencies.}{\fs24  Hunting, Tracking.

\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Recommended Nonweapon Proficiencies.}{\fs24 
 Blind-Fighting, Disguise, Endurance, Intimidation, Juggling, Jumping, Running, Set Snares, Tumbling.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Equipment. }{\fs24 The Huntsman, like the ranger, does
 not like being heavily encumbered. He carries only those things he cannot quickly and cheaply replace and is usually prepared to make the things that cannot be easily replaced. His most valuable piece of equipment is his mind.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Distinctive Appearance.}{\fs24  T
he Huntsman has no distinctive appearance.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Special Benefits.}{\fs24 
 The Huntsman gains an automatic +10% to both his Move Silently and Hide in Shadows skills; this applies to both city and wilderness settings. Because he has spent so much time learning stealth
, this is in addition to his regular modifiers for high Dexterity and race.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {\fs24    \tab \tab The Huntsman also takes a smaller penalty to his Tracking proficiency than other nonrangers. His life has been spent \tab \tab 
in the hunt, and he therefore is more familiar with the signs of the forest than many others.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Special Hindrances.}{\fs24 
 Although the Huntsman fetches those who need fetching, he is not regarded well. His trade is in flesh, and people dislike his company. He receives a \endash 2 reaction penalty when dealing with good-ali
gned people. In evil society, they hate him, even if he is evil, because he and his kind are responsible for the capture of friends and allies. He receives a \endash 2 penalty there as well.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {\fs24    \tab \tab The Huntsman may never take the Read Languages ability available to most thieves. His style of life does not require \tab \tab 
learning new languages and, indeed, forces him to be constantly on the move. He has not the time.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Wealth Options.}{\fs24 
 The Huntsman begins play with 30 to 180 (3d6x10) gp. He can spend this money however he wishes.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Suggested Elf Subraces.}{\fs24  All.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {\fs24 
\par }{\b\fs24\cf13 Fighter/Mage/Thief Kits
\par }{\fs24 
\par The most eclectic of elf PCs, the warrior/mage/thief class is both the most free and the most limited
. While options are nearly limitless for these kits, it takes a lot of doing to get there. But elves have much time on their hands, and they don't mind the "short" wait required to reach these goals.
\par 
\par }{\b\fs24 COLLECTOR
\par }{\fs24 Occasionally, humans will come into possession of items that either aren't theirs or are too dangerous for these short-lived beings to have. The Collector is there to make sure these things return to elf hands.
\par    \tab The Collector must have a 13 Intelligence and 15 Charisma, for she must deal with both esoteric knowledge and people.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Role.}{\fs24 
 The Collector's role in life is to retrieve things from dangerous places. Whether this item is a stolen suit of elven plate armor or an ancient, unearthed artifact, the Collector will get it back. When humans seem i
n danger of destroying things of beauty or of historical power, the Collector makes sure those objects are spirited away to safety.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {\fs24    \tab \tab The Collector is not only a thief, but an archaeologist as well. She uses all her classes' skills to retrieve the items from \tab \tab 
wherever they lie, even deep beneath the earth, then keeps them from the hands of the elves' enemies.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Secondary Skills.}{\fs24 
 Any. Artist, Jeweler, and Historian/Sage are especially appropriate.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Weapon Proficiencies.}{\fs24  }{\i\fs24 Bonus:}{\fs24 
 None. }{\i\fs24 Recommended:}{\fs24  Short bow, dagger, short sword, whip, and small weapons that can fit into the tight places into which a Collector must sometimes venture.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Bonus Nonweapon Proficiencies.}{\fs24 
 Ancient History, Engineering.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Recommended Nonweapon Proficiencies.}{\fs24  Appraising, A
rtistic Ability, Gem Cutting, Jumping, Modern Languages, Musical Instrument, Rope Use, Stonemasonry, Tightrope Walking.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Equipment.}{\fs24 
 The Collector is never far from her archaeological tools and burglary equipment. She is prepared to dig in the earth, venture into a fortress, or swing between two tall towers. She is ready for nearly any eventuality in the quest of her prize.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Distinctive Appearance.}{\fs24 
 Although they might imagine they are sharply dressed, Collectors are often rumpled and disheveled, more tha
n likely covered with the dust and muck of their most recent adventure. Though they may wear fashionable clothing, Collectors simply cannot keep clothing neat and clean. There are always exceptions but, for the most part, Collectors appear musty and dirty
.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Special Benefits.}{\fs24 
 The Collector, because of her research into the histories of artifacts and ancient civilizations, has a chance to know something about nearly every important magic item on her world. If she can lay her hands on an object and study it,
 she can attempt to identify it, much like the bard's ability.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {\fs24    \tab \tab Collectors have a 5% chance per two levels (that is, 5% at 1st to 2nd level, 10% at 3rd to 4th level, and so forth) to \tab \tab 
identify an item's history, purpose, and alignment (if it has one). The only idea a Collector has of an item's power lies \tab \tab within the pages of the histories the Collector has read.
\par    \tab \tab This chance increases (at the DM's discretion) if the Collector has access to a research facility with an extensive \tab \tab collection of book
s on magical items and artifacts. If not, there is no bonus. The Collector spends 1d3 days finding \tab \tab the pertinent information.
\par    \tab \tab Likewise, the Collector can find information leading to the discovery of such magical items, which is the main part of \tab \tab he
r job. If she spends a week or more in research, depending on the rarity of the item and the difficulty of finding it, \tab \tab she can discover the general area in which to begin her search.
\par    \tab \tab The Collector is an expert at rumor gathering. By spending 10d100 gp and making a successful Intelligence and \tab \tab Charisma check, the Collector can usually get a lead on where an item lies. Sometimes the information received is as \tab 
\tab vague as a general location; sometimes it is as specific as the exact hiding place. Now all the Collector needs to do is \tab \tab to find a way past all the protections. . . .
\par    \tab \tab Fortunately, Collectors gain a +10% bonus to their Find/Remove Traps skill. It is important to remember that finding \tab \tab a trap and removing a trap requires two separate rolls
. Because so many of the old places are fraught with peril, the \tab \tab Collectors have found this benefit to be of inestimable value.
\par    \tab \tab Finally, Collectors are rather lucky elves. Once a day, they may +1 or \endash 1 from one of their rolls, if they desire. The \tab \tab m
odification may be to any roll, including attack rolls, damage rolls, saving throws, and so forth. It cannot be used in \tab \tab character creation, nor can it be saved from day to day! The player must declare that a modification is being used \tab \tab 
before the roll is actually made or the roll is void.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Special Hindrances.}{\fs24 
 Although Collectors are, for the most part, decent people, they receive a \endash 2 reaction penalty. The penalty reflects their tendency to lecture, forgetting that others do not share their passion for digging in the earth.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {\fs24    \tab \tab Far more hindering is the fact that Collectors will }{\i\fs24 never}{\fs24  knowingly use a magically charged item. They are afraid that \tab \tab 
the use of such items might deplete its last charge; their purpose is to ensure the preservation of such items. They are \tab \tab cautious around all other magical items unless certain they are not charged or are heavily charged.
\par    \tab \tab Furthermore, Collectors will never perform an action that is potentially destructive to a magical item unless it is the \tab \tab 
only way to save their own lives and the lives of their companions. Even then, they will hesitate, agonizing over the \tab \tab loss to the world.
\par    \tab \tab Collectors even have a difficult time destroying sentient, earth-shaking artifacts of utter evil. Although they know the \tab \tab 
artifact is irredeemably evil, they can barely bring themselves to destroy an item that has plagued the history of the \tab \tab world.
\par    \tab \tab If she has been persuaded to eliminate an item or after she has destroyed an item to save a life, the Collector will go \tab \tab 
into a state of deep unhappiness, lasting for at least a week. During this time, she is not capable of intelligent \tab \tab discussion and her saves and attack rolls are all at \endash 2. Note that this depression has a basis: If the Collector destroys 
\tab \tab more than five items during her career or simply allows five such items to be destroyed, she will lose all of the benefits \tab \tab of this kit.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Wealth Options.}{\fs24  The Collec
tor begins with 30 to 240 (3d8x10) gp. At least half of this money must be spent on house-and lock-breaking equipment and on excavating tools such as shovels and picks. The rest of the money can be spent as the character desires.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Suggested Elf Subraces.}{\fs24 
 Aquatic elf, grey elf, high elf.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {\fs24   
\par }{\b\fs24 INFILTRATOR
\par }{\fs24 The Infiltrator is the very model of an elf scout. Whether in urban or wilderness situations, the Infiltrator is the master of stealth and disguise.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Role.}{\fs24 
 When elves need quick and reliable information wi
th a minimum of fuss, they call on an Infiltrator. The Infiltrators' motto is "If it's a secret, it's not." Sometimes, the Infiltrator will gain information simply for the sheer joy of knowing it. Although this is a typically elven trait, only the Infiltr
ators go to such an extent to learn a secret.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Secondary Skills.}{\fs24  Any.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Weapon Proficiencies.}{\fs24 
 There are no bonus weapon proficiencies for this kit.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Bonus Nonweapon Proficiencies.}{\fs24 
 Disguise, Forgery, Information Gathering, Observation, Tightrope Walking.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Recommended Nonweapon Proficiencies.}{\fs24 
 Ancient History, Etiquette, Modern Language, Reading Lips.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Equipment.}{\fs24 
 Every Infiltrator must have a good disguise kit. Otherwise, they are free to choose whatever equipment they like.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Distinctive Appearance.}{\fs24  
The only thing distinctive about the appearance of an Infiltrator is that he has no distinctive appearance. Elves can, by word of mouth, sometimes find out who the Infiltrators are, but only if the Infiltrator wishes to be found.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Special Benefits.}{\fs24  One o
f the special benefits the Infiltrator receives is the large number of bonus nonweapon proficiencies. Please note that some of these appear }{\i\fs24 in The Complete Thief's Handbook.}{\fs24 
 These all enable him to carry out his job more effectively, and he is so practiced in these proficiencies that he gains a +1 bonus when he uses one of them.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {\fs24 \tab \tab When an Infiltrator wishes to appear as a member of another race, he can usually pass himself off as a tall dwarf or a \tab \tab 
short human with only a \endash 4 penalty. This bonus increases by +1 for every four levels the Infiltrator obtains in his most \tab \tab expensive class. That is, it increases when he reaches 10,000 experience points in all three classes, making the 
\tab \tab Infiltrator a 4th-level fighter/4th-level mage/5th-level thief. Note that this applies only to the bonus proficiencies given \tab \tab by the kit; it doesn't apply to either the recommended or the character-chosen proficiencies.
\par    \tab \tab The Infiltrator also gains a +10% bonus to the two thief skills of his choice. This is a one-time only bonus and cannot \tab \tab be changed later in the Infiltrator's career.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Special Hindrances.}{\fs24 
 The Infiltrator spends so much time taking on the roles of other people that he may begin to lose his own sense of identity. Even the reverie, which ordinarily reinforces an elf's identity, may not help prevent his sense of self slipping away.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {\fs24    \tab \tab Therefore, for each level an Infiltrator acquires, he loses 10% from his ordinary resistance to }{\i\fs24 charm}{\fs24 -related and }{\i\fs24 sleep
}{\fs24  \tab \tab spells. This decreases his 90% resistance downward, to a minimum of 30%. Thus, until the point when the 8th level is \tab \tab achieved, Infiltrators will lose 10% of their resistance at each level.
\par    \tab \tab Such loss of self means that the Infiltrator will never be as sure of himself as an ordinary elf, although his sense of self \tab \tab 
will still be stronger than that of a human. Unless he is acting a role, the Infiltrator will be somewhat unsure of himself \tab \tab and may question his own motives.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Wealth Options.}{\fs24 
 The Infiltrator begins play with 40 to 140 (2d6+2\'b410) gp. This money can be spent however desired.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Suggested Elf Subraces.}{\fs24 
 Drow, high elf, sylvan elf.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {\fs24 
\par }{\b\fs24\cf13 A Kit for Any Class
\par 
\par }{\fs24 Every elf has the capability to achieve some of the same ends, although in different ways. The following is a classwide kit that any elf can take, regardless of profession, class, or multiclass combination.
\par 
\par }{\b\fs24 
\par UNDEAD SLAYER}{\fs24 
\par As elves loathe the undead, it is only logical that they develop methods to combat the undead menace. Whether they stay behind to protect elf homes from ravening undead hordes or actively seek out the unliving to destroy them in their foul nests, the Unde
ad Slayers learn all they can about their wretched foes.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Role.}{\fs24 
 The Undead Slayers are schooled in the ways of the undead, seeking to destroy undead monsters wherever they can find them.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Secondary Skills.}{\fs24 
 Any. Undead Slayers are drawn from all lots in life.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Weapon Proficiencies.}{\fs24  }{\i\fs24 Bonus:}{\fs24 
 One bludgeoning weapon of Medium size, as long as it is allowed by the initial class.}{\i\fs24  Recommended:}{\fs24  A piercing or slashing weapon to complement the bludgeoning weapon.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Bonus Nonweapon Proficiencies.}{\fs24  Blind-fighting.

\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Recommended Nonweapon Proficiencies.}{\fs24 
 Healing, Herbalism, Ancient History, Local History, Ancient Languages, Survival.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Equipment.}{\fs24 
 Every Undead Slayer carries the common items necessary for this trade. Most of them carry backpacks containing at least a 
mirror, two vials of holy water (if not more), several sharpened stakes, holy symbols, tinder for torches, and so forth. For weapons, if their class allows, they carry at least two silver weapons, one each of piercing and bludgeoning type, as well as ordi
nary weapons.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Distinctive Appearance.}{\fs24 
 Most Undead Slayers have a grim, determined look\emdash the result of the grisly nature of their work. These elves have lost the typical elven enjoyment of life, for they have become obsessed with death and the undead.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Special Benefits.}{\fs24 
 Undead Slayers have chosen a particular form of undead to combat and have researched it thoroughly. They know every nuance and variation between the various members of that species. For this reason, Undead Slayers, if properly prepared, ga
in a +2 to attack rolls and to damage against their chosen undead foes.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {\fs24    \tab \tab Undead Slayers hunt the undead more easily than most. They know the signs of undead infestations and can trace \tab \tab 
them back to their sources. Their keen elven senses are honed to detect the unnatural rhythms of undead, and they \tab \tab can therefore find their lairs.
\par    \tab \tab This does not mean that they can find a distant vampire's secret lair. Instead, by listening to rumors and observing the \tab \tab local phenomena, they can find the general are
a where the lair might be. Then they may search for the creature more \tab \tab personally.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f3 \loch\af3\dbch\af0\hich\f3 \'b7\tab}}\pard \fi-360\li720\nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\ilvl0\ls1\pnrnot0\pnf3\pnindent360 {\pntxtb \'b7}}\ls1\adjustright {\b\fs24 Special Hindrances.}{\fs24 
 Although they can fight other foes, the Slayers will never turn down a chance to eliminate an undead enemy. While this does not mean charging blindly
 into battle, they will not hesitate to sacrifice their lives if it means the undead will perish. They will never back away from the opportunity to rid the world of these blasphemous creations, regardless of the cost to themselves.
\par }\pard \nowidctlpar\tx-720\tx360{\*\pn \pnlvlcont\ilvl0\ls0\pnrnot0\pndec }\adjustright {\fs24    \tab \tab Mindless undead are rather low on their list of priorities for destruction. Skeletons and zombies do not arouse the \tab \tab 
hatred and loathing of the Undead Slayer as much as sentient undead do. Anything with a mind raises the hackles and \tab \tab the anger of the Undead Slayer.
\par    \tab \tab Such is the Undead Slayers' devotion to their cause that they will plan ways to destroy even those undead who have \tab \tab proved themselves friendly. Dealing with a good or neutral lich, for example, is impossible for an Undead Slayer. 
\tab \tab Simply knowing of the existence of such an abomination is enough for this character to seek ways to annihilate it.
