\par }{\fs24 
\par Most of the magical items listed in this chapter are rare and will not be found lying ar
ound in just any hoard. Instead, they can be incorporated into a campaign (preferably with elven overtones) to suit the Dungeon Master's purposes. These items should never be just random treasure. If they are going to be used in a campaign, there must def
initely be a reason for their inclusion.
\par 
\par }{\b\fs24\cf13 Swords and Armor
\par }{\fs24 
\par Despite being relatively peaceful folk, elves have a tremendous knowledge of war and warfare. But even in war, the elves find time to be artistic\emdash as evidenced by the stunning beauty of their weaponry and protection.
\par    \tab 
Elven swords are often legendary, especially those produced by the crafters of the early millenia. These were originally created to battle titanic beings of old, creatures who could be slain only if powerful magicks were cast upon a blade and armor given 
mighty protections.
\par    \tab Because of the threat these beings posed to the world, elf crafters rose to the challenge, creating artifacts of wondrous power. Even though the monsters they were created to destroy have long since passed from the world, the blades 
themselves are rumored to have survived the toll of the ages. Even now, some find their way into the hands of humans.
\par    \tab Some races have spread the rumor that, because of superior elven craftsmanship, these blades continue to }{\i\fs24 grow }{\fs24 in power through the age
s, rather than decrease as so many magical items do. If this is indeed true, then a weapon from the long-ago Elfwar would have since become a weapon of awesome might. In the right hands, such a weapon could work wondrous good. And in the wrong hands? . . 
. Untold devastation.
